-- в”Ђв”Ђ Alarm Clock в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Alarm Clock is a free, open-source alarm and timer applet for Linux desktops that use an AppIndicator (GNOME, Unity, and similar panels), letting users schedule repeatable alarms and countdown timers from a system tray icon.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$open-source$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE(NULL, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(NULL, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE(NULL, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Alarm Clock Applet 2026: Free Linux Alarm Tool Guide$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Alarm Clock is a free, open-source GNOME/Linux applet for scheduling alarms and timers from your system tray. See features, setup, and how it compares.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Alarm Clock (also referenced as Alarm Clock Applet) is a free and open-source desktop utility for Linux systems that provides a fully-featured alarm clock through an AppIndicator, the small icon that sits in a system tray or top panel on GNOME, Unity, and similar desktop environments. It is not a commercial SaaS product and has no parent company: it is maintained entirely by volunteer developers on GitHub under the alarm-clock-applet organization, distributed under the GPL-2.0 open-source license, and written primarily in C with a CMake build system. The project supports two scheduling types, Clocks, which ring at a specific time of day and can repeat on chosen days of the week, and Timers, which count down from a specified duration, for example for cooking or work-interval reminders. When an alarm fires, the applet can play a bundled sound, launch a user-chosen audio file, or start a preferred music player, and both alarms and timers can be snoozed or dismissed directly from the tray icon's right-click menu, without needing to bring a separate window into focus. After a period of limited activity, the project was picked up by a new maintainer, tatokis, in January 2023, who ported the codebase from GTK 2 to GTK 3 (requiring GTK 3.22.30 or newer), refreshed dependency handling for libnotify, GStreamer, and Ayatana AppIndicator, and set a minimum supported baseline of Ubuntu 18.04 and comparable distributions. The most recent tagged release, version 0.4.1 ('Happy New Year'), shipped on January 9, 2023, and development continues on GitHub with several hundred commits and an active issue tracker. Because there is no company behind it, there is no pricing, subscription, or licensing fee: the source code is free to download, compile, and modify, and it is also packaged for easy installation via Launchpad PPAs and some Linux distribution repositories. Alarm Clock competes conceptually with built-in GNOME Clocks, KDE's alarm tools, or cron-based scripting, but its niche is being a lightweight, panel-native, AppIndicator-first alarm applet for users who specifically want a tray-accessible alarm rather than a full desktop application. It is best suited to Linux desktop users, particularly on Ubuntu-derived and GNOME-family distributions, who want simple, always-visible alarm and timer functionality without installing a heavier scheduling suite.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'e730f7fb-ce8a-45ee-a2f2-2805eba89d8f';

